      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies! I get a little carried away with the yard work metaphors; I've got the goblin urge for everything, honestly. The \"scouting party\" and \"blue-skinned friends\" were just my way of saying you need to *check* your soil, like sending out a tiny reconnaissance squad to see what the dirt is up to. You want to keep your blueberry bushes happy, which means they thrive in acidic conditions, ideally aiming for a soil pH between 4.5 and 5.5. If your soil is trending too high, like above 6.0, those crucial nutrients become almost locked away, making the plant starve even when the soil looks rich. It's like if you offered a tiny, hungry goblin a pile of shiny trinkets, but they were all made of stone—they can't eat them!\n\nIf you suspect high pH, you can correct it by adding elemental sulfur or using peat moss, which is highly acidic. This process takes time, so don't expect an instant fix; it's more of a slow, persistent campaign against alkalinity. Monitoring the pH regularly is key, so you can adjust before the yellowing turns into a full-blown, sad, dro",
